body:
Thanks for taking the time to report this.

Can you please attach an example that shows the issue or missing feature?  (Must be openly licensed, completely self-contained so can directly run what you provide. Ideally use test_regress format, see https://veripool.org/guide/latest/contributing.html?highlight=test_regress#reporting-bugs)

```systemverilog
package ipkg;
  typedef interface class iclass;

  interface class iclass;
    pure virtual function void doit();
  endclass
endpackage

package epkg;
  interface class cclass2 extends ipkg::iclass;
    pure virtual function void doit2();
  endclass

  class cclass implements cclass2;
    virtual function void doit();
        $display("doit");
    endfunction
    virtual function void doit2();
        $display("doit2");
    endfunction
  endclass
endpackage

module top;
  import epkg::*;

  initial begin
    automatic cclass c = new();
    c.doit();
  end
endmodule
```

The example above uses a package-rooted reference to `ipkg::iclass` when extending it. 

What output from that test indicates it is wrong, and what is the correct or expected output?  (Or, please make test self-checking if possible.)

This results in the following error:
```
verilator --binary iclass.sv 
%Error: iclass.sv:5:13: Interface class shall not be nested within another interface class. (IEEE 1800-2023 8.26)
    5 |   interface class iclass;
      |             ^~~~~
        ... See the manual at https://verilator.org/verilator_doc.html?v=5.041 for more assistance.
%Error: Exiting due to 1 error(s)
```

Verilator <= 5.032 and commerical toolchains accept this without error.

Explicitly importing the referenced package appears to be a workaround. For example:

```
package epkg;
  import ipkg::*; // Workaround error with package-rooted reference
  interface class cclass2 extends ipkg::iclass;
    pure virtual function void doit2();
  endclass

```

What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?

```
verilator --binary iclass.sv
```

What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?  Did you try it with other simulators?

```
Verilator 5.041 devel rev v5.040-288-g8785086bc
```

What OS and distribution are you using? Ubuntu 24.04

May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself? Possibly, depending on how involved the issue is.

(Please avoid attaching screenshots that show text - you can convert images to text using e.g. https://ocr.space)

